title: Best home deals at the Kohl's Friends and Family sale today
description: Save up to $150 on bedding, cleaning products and cooking tools, and rack up tons of Kohl's Cash while you do it.

title: Icelandic volcano erupts yet again, nearby town evacuated
description: Lava spewed Saturday from a new volcanic fissure on Iceland's Reykjanes peninsula, the fourth eruption to hit the area​ since December, authorities said.

title: When do March Madness brackets come out? Key dates and times for the 2024 NCAA tournament
description: Score all the information you need to watch Selection Sunday and the 2024 NCAA college basketball tournament.

title: Judge rules that Miami Beach's spring break midnight curfew stays after 3 nightclubs file complaint against city
description: Peter D'Oench will have more on CBS News Miami tonight at 11 p.m on-air and online.

title: Venezuela's President Nicolas Maduro clinches nomination; seeks third term
description: Nicolas Maduro accepted the official nomination of the ruling PSUV party on Saturday.

title: 3/16: CBS Saturday Morning
description: First maritime aid shipment reaches Gaza amid rift between Biden, Netanyahu; Unusual pool cleaning group does the task for a surprising fee.

title: Celine Dion shares health update in rare photo with sons
description: Celine Dion said in her post that March 15 was International Stiff-Person Syndrome Awareness Day.

title: U.S. government charter flights to evacuate citizens from Haiti
description: USAID said some 5.5 million people in Haiti - nearly half the population - need humanitarian aid​.

title: Meet Hansel Enmanuel, the NCAA standout who lets nothing get in his way
description: Hansel Enmanuel gained worldwide recognition last year when he kicked off his collegiate basketball career at Northwestern State University. This year, he transferred to Austin Peay State University to nearly double his average playing time and rank second in blocked shots. And he's doing it all with one arm. Dana Jacobson has more on his story.

title: Blind 750-pound alligator named Albert seized from New York home
description: Self-proclaimed owner Tony Cavallaro said he treated his pet alligator Albert "than most people take care of their kids."

title: The Dish: Chicago restaurants
description: We explore Chicago’s delicious eats, from a Hyde Park spot celebrating Southern food and Black culture to a steakhouse in West Loop with a unique cooking method. Watch these stories and more on "The Dish."

title: Chef at Manhattan's premier Nordic restaurant makes new opportunities for others
description: Chef Emma Bengtsson is the first Swedish female chef to earn 2 Michelin stars and the most recent recipient of the organization's Mentor Chef Award. Born in Sweden, Bengtsson developed a taste for her grandmother's cooking and takes pride in sharing it with those lucky enough to get a seat at her Manhattan restaurant Aquavit.

title: Traveling art exhibit showcases African-American history
description: The Kinsey Collection is the largest private holding of African-American art and artifacts. It's a family affair as the show travels the world. Michelle Miller visited the latest exhibition in Houston to talk about how it all began.

title: Eye on America: Successful eye transplant, and the healing power of breathing
description: In New York, we speak with the patient and medical team behind the first successful eye transplant. Then in Arizona, we get a firsthand look at a breathing technique that proponents claim can create a healing psychedelic state without any drugs. Watch these stories and more on "Eye on America" with host Michelle Miller.

title: Saturday Sessions: Glen Hansard performs "Bearing Witness"
description: The Grammy-nominated, Oscar-winning Irish singer-songwriter Glen Hansard first garnered attention in 1990 as front man of the Irish band The Frames, then catapulted to fame as the star of 2007's movie "Once," which earned him an Academy Award for Best Original Song. Hansard is now out with his fifth studio solo album, "All That Was East is West of Me Now." Now, here is Glen Hansard with "Bearing Witness."

title: Saturday Sessions: Glen Hansard performs "The Feast Of St. John"
description: The Grammy-nominated, Oscar-winning Irish singer-songwriter Glen Hansard first garnered attention in 1990 as front man of the Irish band The Frames, then catapulted to fame as the star of 2007's movie "Once," which earned him an Academy Award for Best Original Song. Hansard is now out with his fifth studio solo album, "All That Was East is West of Me Now." Now, here is Glen Hansard with "The Feast Of St. John."

title: Saturday Sessions: Glen Hansard performs "There's No Mountain"
description: The Grammy-nominated, Oscar-winning Irish singer-songwriter Glen Hansard first garnered attention in 1990 as front man of the Irish band The Frames, then catapulted to fame as the star of 2007's movie "Once," which earned him an Academy Award for Best Original Song. Hansard is now out with his fifth studio solo album, "All That Was East is West of Me Now." Now, here is Glen Hansard with "There's No Mountain."

title: Wales elects Vaughan Gething, first Black national leader in Europe
description: Gething will be the first Black leader of a government in the U.K. - and, by some definitions, of any European country.

title: Unusual pool cleaning group does the task for a surprising fee
description: A group of California skateboarders are happy to clean your drained pool - if they can bring their boards. The group cleans pools, then uses them for the thrilling sport of pool skateboarding.

title: Glen Hansard talks new album and long music career
description: Over his long career, Irish singer-songwriter Glen Hansard has taken home an Oscar and been nominated for multiple Grammy Awards. He sat down recently with Jeff Glor to talk about his career, fatherhood and the unique way he developed his most recent album "All That Was East Is West of Me Now."

title: The Uplift: Unconditional love
description: A couple shares their blended family's message of unconditional love. A TikTok star named Alex the Great gets widespread attention. Plus, go inside a museum of oddities.

title: Multiple people shot in Falls Township, Pa.: residents asked to shelter-in-place
description: Bucks County emergency dispatch confirmed there is a shelter-in-place in effect in Falls Township, Pa.

title: 50 women on ski trip stranded by snowstorm, trapped in bus overnight
description: A weekly ski trip for about 50 women from the Denver area were trapped on a bus for about 22 hours after being stuck in a snowstorm.

title: Fani Willis remains on Georgia election interference case after Nathan Wade resigns
description: Fulton County district attorney Fani Willis will remain on Georgia's election interference case against former president Donald Trump after special prosecutor Nathan Wade resigns following a judge's ultimatum. The judge said that either Willis or Wade must resign, but ruled that Trump and his legal team failed to provide a conflict of interest where Willis benefitted from her year-long romantic relationship with Wade.

title: Home buying might be cheaper for millions soon as realtor association settles lawsuits
description: The National Association of Realtors, which represents more than a million real estate agents nationwide, settled a number of lawsuits Friday. One of the conditions of the agreement is that rules on commissions for agents brokering a home sale will be eliminated, meaning that the standard 5% to 6% commission rate could be gone as soon as this summer.

title: Humanitarian crisis worsens in Haiti
description: The humanitarian crisis in Haiti is worsening as escalating gang violence rips the Caribbean nation apart. On Friday, the U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken said a plan to create a transitional presidential council on the island is moving forward to try and restore stability as political turmoil drives a rise in hunger.

title: Measles infections are on the rise, with more cases so far in 2024 than all of last year
description: There have been more measles cases reported so far in 2024 than all of 2023, with more than 60 confirmed or suspected cases currently recorded. Chicago has 12 confirmed cases, including 10 linked to a migrant shelter, causing the city to enact new policies amid the outbreak.

title: Exclusive discounts from CBS Mornings Deals
description: On this edition of CBS Mornings Deals, Ashley Bellman shows some items that might just become essentials in your everyday life. Visit cbsdeals.com to take advantage of these exclusive deals today. CBS earns commissions on purchases made through cbsdeals.com.

title: First maritime aid shipment reaches Gaza amid rift between Biden, Netanyahu
description: The first maritime aid shipment has reached Gaza, bringing 200 tons of desperately needed food to the war-ravaged territory. The move comes amid a deepening rift between President Joe Biden and Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu. On Friday, Netanyahu approved an Israeli military plan for a ground invasion of Rafah, which the White House said it had not been briefed on and could not support without a credible proposal to limit civilian loss.

title: The White House says it is "cautiously optimistic" about Gaza cease-fire amid negotiations
description: The White House says it is "cautiously optimistic" about a cease-fire in Gaza after a new Hamas proposal called for a six-week pause in fighting. Israel rejected the proposal, but said it will send a team of negotiators to Qatar this week.

title: Eye Opener: New concerns after Boeing plane lands with missing panel
description: There’s more trouble from Being after a United flight was found to have a missing panel. Meanwhile, climate protestors disrupted a Broadway play on Thursday night. All that and all that matters in today’s Eye Opener.

title: Testosterone websites promote off-label use despite FDA ad ban
description: Most healthy men produce sufficient testosterone as they age. Yet online ads and telehealth sites are promoting testosterone drugs with flawed promises of boosting libido and busting stomach fat.

title: Supreme Court to hear case involving government pressure to remove social media content
description: The Supreme Court on Monday will hear two cases that involve "jawboning," or informal pressure by the government on an intermediary to take certain actions that will suppress speech.

title: Russian voting continues in election preordained to extend Putin's rule
description: Vladimir Putin faces no serious challengers in the election, which is set to formally grant him six more years of power.

title: Mega Millions jackpot grows to an estimated $875 million
description: There has not been a Mega Millions jackpot winner​ since Dec. 8.

title: 3/15: CBS Evening News
description: At least 3 killed, dozens injured as tornadoes hit Midwest; How a Maine 8-year-old inadvertently became a fashion trendsetter at his school

title: Winning numbers drawn for estimated $815 million Mega Millions jackpot
description: There has not been a Mega Millions jackpot winner​ since Dec. 8.

title: 3/15: CBS News Weekender
description: Lana Zak reports on the Fulton County prosecutor stepping down from the Georgia election interference case, a story of survival after tornadoes in Ohio, and what to make of Russia's presidential election.

title: Proposed California bill would ban Flamin' Hot Cheetos in schools
description: If you're a Flamin' Hot Cheetos fan in California, there might be some bad news on the way. A new bill proposed in the California State Assembly is seeking to stop all schools from selling or providing foods with artificial color dyes and titanium dioxide due to their potentially negative health effects.

title: How a Maine 8-year-old inadvertently became a fashion trendsetter
description: Most 8-year-old boys don't get dressed to the nines. But James Ramage of Chelsea, Maine, loves to dress for third-grade success.

title: 2024 NAACP Image Award winners announced ahead of show
description: The first round of NAACP Image Award winners has been announced ahead of Saturday's show, and CBS News has an inside look at the honorees. Aba Blankson, chief marketing and communications officer for the NAACP, joins to preview the event.

title: What to watch in Russia's 2024 presidential election
description: Russia's weekend-long presidential election is expected to deliver another term in office to Vladimir Putin. Maria Snegovaya, senior fellow at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, joins CBS News to discuss how the opposition is trying to break through, and what it all means for the war in Ukraine.

title: Predicting top seeds for 2024 men's NCAA Tournament
description: March Madness is less than a week away, but the NCAA committees still need to cement the field on Selection Sunday. Brian Bennett, senior editor at "The Athletic," joins CBS News to discuss what to know before the Big Dance.

title: United flight from San Francisco lands in Oregon with fuselage panel missing
description: It was only during a "post-landing airline inspection" that the missing panel was discovered, the FAA said.

title: Classified records, Haiti and Israel: Weekly national security recap
description: Questions about the presidential handling of classified documents, growing gang violence in Haiti, and a call for Israeli leadership change are among the top national security stories this week. CBS News national security contributor Sam Vinograd joins to break it all down.

title: Midwest tornado survivors recount destructive storms
description: Several states across the Midwest are dealing with the aftermath of a series of tornadoes, one of which killed three people in Ohio. CBS News correspondent Roxana Saberi spoke with survivors.

title: What Nathan Wade resigning means for Fani Willis' Trump case
description: Special prosecutor Nathan Wade stepped down Friday from the Georgia election interference case against former President Donald Trump. The move came hours after a judge ruled Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis could stay on the case if Wade resigned. CBS News' Nikole Killion and Daniel Klaidman have the latest.

title: Acting Labor Secretary Julie Su still hopeful she'll be confirmed for top job
description: On "The Takeout" podcast this week, Acting Labor Secretary Julie Su said she's still hopeful she'll be confirmed for the top job, though she's been waiting for over a year.

title: How a Maine 8-year-old inadvertently became a fashion trendsetter at his school
description: Most 8-year-old boys don't get dressed to the nines. But James Ramage of Chelsea, Maine, loves to dress for third-grade success. Steve Hartmans has his story in "On the Road."

title: National Association of Realtors agrees to eliminate rules on commissions
description: As part of a settlement Friday in a landmark antitrust lawsuit, the National Association of Realtors has agreed to eliminate rules on commissions, meaning buyers and sellers would be able to negotiate fees with realtors.

title: Cease-fire talks underway as groups rush aid into Gaza
description: A top White House official says he's cautiously optimistic that cease-fire talks between Israel and Hamas are moving in the right direction. Chris Livesay reports on what Hamas is proposing and efforts to get more aid into the Gaza Strip.

title: Chicago dealing with measles outbreak
description: Chicago is the latest city to be hit with a measles outbreak. There are 12 confirmed cases so far, including 10 connected to the city's largest migrant center. Sabrina Franza reports on the city's efforts to stop the spread.

title: Ex-FBI informant charged with lying about Bidens called a "fraudster" in prior case
description: In a CBS News investigation, Scott MacFarlane takes a look at one of House Republicans' key witnesses, ex-FBI informant Alexander Smirnov, who is now charged with lying to investigators about President Biden's business dealings. Smirnov was accused of being "a liar and a fraudster" in a previous case.

title: Fulton County prosecutor resigns from Trump case after judge's ultimatum
description: Fulton County prosecutor Nathan Wade resigned Friday after a judge ruled that District Attorney Fani Willis can stay on former President Donald Trump's Georgia election interference case if Wade steps aside. Nikole Killion has details.
